{
  "text": "The opening of the Bering Strait may also have wider implications on climate. For example, a recent study [CITATION_1] suggests that abrupt climate change events evident in the Greenland ice core record between 70 and 11 kyr bp (ref. [CITATION_2] ) may be related to the closing of the Bering Strait. Although the Bering Strait itself may not directly control the surface climate change, the effect of the strait on the transport of the fresh Pacific water into the Arctic and North Atlantic does influence the MOC strength, and consequently can modulate Earth's climate. Therefore, climate changes and the Bering Strait may well have been intimately linked throughout the Late Pleistocene ice age.",
  "citation_candidates": [
